[1] Michigan
Date: Tue 15 Dec 2015
Source: WOOD TV [edited]
http://woodtv.com/2015/12/15/chickenpox-outbreak-sparks-warning-from-mi-health-officials/


[Michigan] state health officials are urging parents to ensure their children are up-to-date on vaccines after chickenpox outbreaks in several counties, including 2 in West Michigan. The Michigan Department of Health and Human Services [MDHHS] says Calhoun, Muskegon, Grand Traverse, and Wayne counties have reported chickenpox outbreaks in recent weeks. The cases have mainly involved unvaccinated children in school settings.

Health officials say the virus was severe enough that several children were hospitalized.

The varicella virus, commonly known as chickenpox is caused by a virus in the herpes family. The itchy, blistery rash that is the hallmark of chickenpox may be accompanied by fever, fatigue, headache, and loss of appetite. Chickenpox is highly contagious. The virus is spread through coughing, sneezing, and contaminated surfaces.

According to the MDHHS, before the chickenpox vaccine became widely utilized, an estimated 4 million Americans contracted chickenpox each year. About 100 of those people died each year.

"Since the introduction of the chickenpox vaccine 20 years ago, the immunization has greatly reduced the incidence of illnesses, hospitalizations, and deaths related to the disease. Michigan has seen a 97 percent decline in chickenpox in that time," said Dr Eden Wells in a news release from the MDHHS. "The best thing you can do to protect your loved ones and community against chickenpox is to make sure your family is immunized."

